You are working on the e-commerce store for JMT International Free Zone Company, a Dubai (UAE)
company importing Ethiopian agri-products (green coffee, sesame, pulses, spices) and selling to
Dubai buyers. The codebase is a fork of NimblePros/eShopOnWeb (ASP.NET Core 10, Clean Architecture).

READ AGENTS.md IN THE REPO ROOT BEFORE ANY CHANGE. It is the source of truth. Summary of the
hard rules:

1. DO NOT rewrite or re-architect. Keep eShopOnWeb's structure as-is. No microservices, no message
   broker, no new ORM, no big refactors. If a refactor seems needed, propose it in a comment — do
   not perform it.

2. Make SMALL, SCOPED changes. One field/page/feature per change. Never produce huge multi-file diffs.

3. All changes ADDITIVE and REVERSIBLE. New DB columns must be nullable or defaulted. Never drop or
   rename existing columns, tables, or public APIs.

4. NEVER commit secrets. Gateway/messaging/API keys and connection strings go in environment
   variables or .NET user secrets — never in code or appsettings or this repo. Use placeholders.

5. Write/UPDATE TESTS for every behavioural change. No test, no merge.

6. Currency is AED only, everywhere.

7. Reuse existing abstractions: EF Core + Ardalis.Specification for data, IEmailSender for email,
   the payment abstraction for checkout. Razor Pages storefront, Blazor admin, SQL Server.

ZONES:
- GREEN (you may drive): branding, copy, seed data, simple additive product fields, tests, docs.
- YELLOW (you draft, human reviews): new pages/components, additive EF migrations, the wholesale
  request-a-quote flow, the IMessageSender SMS/WhatsApp integration, admin screens.
- RED (assist only, human owns line by line, DO NOT finish autonomously): payment/checkout and the
  PayTabs/Telr integration; authentication/authorization/identity/tokens; any money/price/tax/discount
  math; security-sensitive config. For RED tasks, produce a draft, say "RED-zone, human must verify",
  and stop.

OUT OF SCOPE — never build: supplier payments to Ethiopian exporters (that is treasury, not the app),
customs/import logistics, multi-currency, microservices/Kubernetes/brokers.

WORKFLOW: branch from main (never push to main directly), keep PRs focused, build + test before
ready, write a plain-language PR description (what/why/how to test), hand off to the engineering
lead — never merge your own work.
